abstract.value: James J. Comerford was a well-known lawyer and judge in New York City.  He also served as the Chair of the St. Patrick's Day Parade and Celebration Committee in New York City for 19 years.  A recognized historian, his manuscript entitled <emph render="italic">My Kilkenny I.R.A. Days 1916-1921</emph>, along with writings on the history of Ireland are included in the papers as is correspondence between Mr. Comerford and well-known politicians and other public figures in New York and the United States. Many files pertaining to his work in the Ancient Order of Hibernians are included in the collection.

p.value: Published citations should take the following form: <lb/><lb/>Identification of item, date; James J. Comerford Papers; AIA 010; box number; folder number; <lb/>Archives of Irish America, Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives <lb/>Elmer Holmes Bobst Library <lb/>70 Washington Square South <lb/>New York, NY 10012, New York University Libraries.
The James J. Comerford Papers were donated to the Archives of Irish America in 2004 by John Concannon.  The accession number associated with this collection is 1997.051.
Comerford was married to Vera Carr.  They had no children.

Comerford was active in several organizations in New York, notably the Saint Patrick's Day Parade and Celebration Committee and the Ancient Order of Hibernians (AOH).  He was also the editor of the AOH's publication, the <emph render="italic">Hibernian Digest</emph>, and the collection contains several files on his activities in the Order, as well as photographs and negatives used in the <emph render="italic">Digest</emph>.  Newspaper clippings which are quite fragile and brittle with age document Comerford's career and personal life.  Numerous photographs of Judge Comerford and his wife Vera are included in Series II, as are images of Comerford involved in activities pertaining to the St. Patrick's Day Parade, AOH and other associations.
